macros/analysis/m_u_binom_odds/m_u_binom.title: Example
macros/analysis/m_u_binom_odds/m_u_binom.body:
Example
Example 1 Calculate Odds Ratio related only with stratification factors
Example 2 Calculate Odds Ratio and relative risk related without stratification factors

Example 1 Calculate odds ratio related only with stratification factors
Details
This example does the following:
Calculate odds ratio, confidence interval and p-value of odds ratio considering stratification factors for objective response. 
Program
%m_u_binom_odds(inds=   adeff_all
                            , whr= paramcd='TRORESPU' and OTLVBPFL='Y' and PARQUAL='INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR'
                            , pop_flag= ittfl='Y'
                            , trtgrpn= trt01pn
                            , trtgrp= trt01p
                            , trtpair= str(1 2)
                            , trtfmt=
                            , trtref= 2
                            , strata= strat1n strat2n
                            , var=
                            , event=
                            , alpha=
                            , pvalside=
                            , pvdecim=
                            , cidecim=
                            , relcal= N
                            , cltype=
                            , supds=
                            , missval=
                            , ord= 1
                            , deBug= N
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset is a standard ADEFF adam dataset and contains required variables: USUBJID, TRT01PN,TRT01P,AVAL,PARAM,PARAMCD etc. The dataset must include variable AVAL with value of 0 or 1. 

Parameter description

Filter the dataset using either the whr variable, or during data-preprocess of the input dataset and make sure only one PARAMCD is selected. 

The parameter trtpair defines the treatment group pair for analysis and trtref specifies the treatment group that will be used as reference. The trtref should be within trtpair. 

Parameter strata defines the stratification variables to be consifered if any, note that the value type for strata must be numeric.


Output
Generate a dataset named final_odds_1 that contains the odds ratio, odds ratio confidence interval and odds ratio p-value.
If unable to calculate the confidence interval , display text defined by missval will be displayed.
 

Example 2 Calculate odds ratio and relative risk risk difference related without stratification factors
Details
This example does the following:
Calculate odds ratio, confidence interval and p-value of odds ratio along with relative risk estimate and confidence interval, risk difference estimate, confidence interval and p-value without considering stratification factors for objective response.  
Program
%m_u_binom_odds(inds=   adeff_all
                            , whr= paramcd='TRORESPU' and OTLVBPFL='Y' and PARQUAL='INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR'
                            , pop_flag= ittfl='Y'
                            , trtgrpn= trt01pn
                            , trtgrp= trt01p
                            , trtpair= str(1 2)
                            , trtfmt=
                            , trtref= 2
                            , strata=
                            , var=
                            , event=
                            , alpha= 0.1
                            , pvalside= 
                            , pvdecim= 3
                            , cidecim= 3
                            , relcal= Y
                            , cltype=
                            , supds=
                            , missval=
                            , ord= 1
                            , deBug= N
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset is a standard ADEFF adam dataset and contains required variables: USUBJID, TRT01PN,TRT01P,AVAL,PARAM,PARAMCD etc. The dataset must include variable AVAL with value of 0 or 1. 

Parameter description

Filter the dataset using either the whr variable, or during data-preprocess of the input dataset and make sure only one PARAMCD is selected. 

The parameter trtpair defines the treatment group pair for analysis and trtref specifies the treatment group that will be used as reference. The trtref should be within trtpair. 

Note that in order to obtain relative risk and risk difference related calculations, relcal must be set to 'Y'.

pvdecim, cidecim are both set to 3 and in the output dataset, the rounding are corresponding to the decimal places defined.


Output
Generate a dataset named final_odds_1 that contains the odds ratio, odds ratio confidence interval and odds ratio p-value.
If unable to calculate the confidence interval , display text defined by missval will be displayed.
 
Generate a dataset named final_cmh_1 that contains the relative risk estimate and confidence interval, risk difference estimate, confidence interval and p-value.

Example
Example 1 Calculate progression free survival median and rate at different time stamps

Example 1 Calculate progression free survival median and rate at different time stamps
Details
This example does the following:
Calculate progression free survival median statistics and progression free survival rate at different time stamps.
Program
%m_u_km(inds=   adtte
                            , whr= mittfl='Y' and paramcd='TRPROGM' and parqual='INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR'
                            , alpha= 0.05
                            , method= KM
                            , conftype= LOG
                            , trtgrpn= trt01pn
                            , trtgrpnord= 
                            , pair= 1-2
                            , trtgrpn2=
                            , var_time= AVAL
                            , var_status= CNSR
                            , cen_num= 0
                            , evnt_num=
                            , step_list= 160 to 1686 by 160
                            , xdivisor=
                            , plot= 0
                            , outdat_median= final_median
                            , median_label= Progression-free survival (days) [e] [f]
                            , outdat_timelist= final_timelist
                            , timelist_label= Progression-free survival rate [e]
                            , debug_u= N
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset adtte is a standard ADAM adtte dataset that contains the time variable, censor variable and treatment group variable. 

Parameter description

method and conftype should be determined based on SAP, please confirm method with statistician. 

Filter the dataset using either the whr variable, or during data-preprocess of the input dataset and make sure only one PARAMCD is selected.


Output
Generates a dataset named final_median (dataset name defined by outdat_median) that contains the median and 95% confidence interval for progression-free survival.
Display text in col_blocklable column is defined by median_label.
 
Generates a dataset named final_median_t that contains the transposed information same as final_median along with the n percent statistics. 
Display text in col_blocklable column is defined by median_label.

Generates a dataset named final_timelist that contains the progression-free survival rate on different time stamps.

macros/analysis/m_u_cox_logrank/m_u_cox_.title: Example
macros/analysis/m_u_cox_logrank/m_u_cox_.body:
Example
Example 1 Calculate hazard ratio and confidence interval and p-value without by variable
Example 2 Calculate hazard ratio and confidence interval and p-value with by varaible and two alpha values
Example 3 Calculate hazard ratio and confidence interval and p-value with by varaible and two alpha values and not transposed
Example 1 Calculate hazard ratio and confidence interval without by variable
Details
This example does the following:
Calculate hazard ratio and 95% confidence interval for treatment pairs defined by pair without by variable.
Program
%m_u_cox_logrank(inds=   anl
                        ,out            =    final_test
                        ,blocklbl        =    Comparison of treatment groups
                        ,modelkey        =    cox
                        ,transfl        =    Y
                        ,trtgrpn        =    trt01pN        
                        ,var            =    aval
                        ,byvar            =
                        ,alpha            =    
                        ,censor            =
                        ,indicator        =
                        ,ties            =
                        ,pair           =    1-3|2-3
                        ,strata            =    STRAT1 STRAT2                                                                        
                        ,pvalside        =    
                        ,missval        =
                        ,digit          =    2
                        ,cidecimal       =  
                        ,hrlbl          =             
                        ,pvallbl          = 
                        ,cilbl            =  
                        ,prefix         =
                        ,debug            = N
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset adtte is a standard ADAM adtte dataset that contains the time variable, censor variable, treatment group variable and by variable if any. 

Parameter description

Define the treatment group variable using trtgrpn. 

Set modelkey as cox generates statistics only for hazard ratio and confidence interval.

Set treatment group pairs that needs to analyze by defining pair, the treamtment group positioned on second place is used as reference group. 

Specify stratification variables with strata. 


Output
Generate a dataset named final_test (dataset name defined by out) that contains the hazard ratio, 95% confidence interval.
The column for reference group is left blank. 
 

Example 2 Calculate hazard ratio and confidence interval and Pvalue with by variable and two alpha values
Details
This example does the following:
Calculate hazard ratio, 95% and 90% confidence interval for treatment pairs defined by pair and grouped by age.
Program
%m_u_cox_logrank(inds=   anl
                        ,out            =    final_test
                        ,blocklbl        =    Comparison of treatment groups
                        ,modelkey        =    cox|logrank
                        ,transfl        =    Y
                        ,trtgrpn        =    trt01pN        
                        ,var            =    aval
                        ,byvar            =    AGEGR1
                        ,alpha            =    0.05|0.1
                        ,censor            =
                        ,indicator        =
                        ,ties            =
                        ,pair           =    1-3|2-3
                        ,strata            =    STRAT1 STRAT2                                                                        
                        ,pvalside        =    
                        ,missval        =
                        ,digit          =    2
                        ,cidecimal       =  
                        ,hrlbl          =             
                        ,pvallbl          = 
                        ,cilbl            =  
                        ,prefix         =
                        ,debug            = N
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset adtte is a standard ADAM adtte dataset that contains the time variable, censor variable, treatment group variable and by variable if any. 

Parameter description

Define the treatment group variable using trtgrpn. 

Set modelkey as cox|logrank indicating that both hazard ratio related statistics and p-value are required. 

Set treatment group pairs that needs to analyze by defining pair, the treamtment group positioned on second place is used as reference group. 

Specify stratification variables with strata and by variable using byvar. 

Set alpha as 0.05|0.1 calculates results for 95% and 90% confidence interval. 


Output
Generate a dataset named final_test (dataset name defined by out) that contains the hazard ratio, 95% and 90% confidence interval and p-value for each age group. 
The column for reference group is left blank. 
 

Example 3 Calculate hazard ratio and confidence interval and pvalue with by variable and two alpha values and not transposed
Details
This example does the following:
Calculate hazard ratio, 95% and 90% confidence interval for treatment pairs defined by pair and grouped by age.
Program
%m_u_cox_logrank(inds=   anl
                        ,out            =    final_test
                        ,blocklbl        =    Comparison of treatment groups
                        ,modelkey        =    cox|logrank
                        ,transfl        =    N
                        ,trtgrpn        =    trt01pN        
                        ,var            =    aval
                        ,byvar            =    AGEGR1
                        ,alpha            =    0.05|0.1
                        ,censor            =
                        ,indicator        =
                        ,ties            =
                        ,pair           =    1-3|2-3
                        ,strata            =    STRAT1 STRAT2                                                                        
                        ,pvalside        =    
                        ,missval        =
                        ,digit          =    2
                        ,cidecimal       =  
                        ,hrlbl          =             
                        ,pvallbl          = 
                        ,cilbl            =  
                        ,prefix         =
                        ,debug            = N
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset adtte is a standard ADAM adtte dataset that contains the time variable, censor variable, treatment group variable and by variable if any. 

Parameter description

Define the treatment group variable using trtgrpn. 

Set modelkey as cox|logrank indicating that both hazard ratio related statistics and p-value are required. 

Set transfl as N generates dataset that is not transposed. Treatment groups are positioned on rows instead of columns and statistic discriptions are shown as column headers. 

Set treatment group pairs that needs to analyze by defining pair, the treamtment group positioned on second place is used as reference group. 

Specify stratification variables with strata and by variable using byvar. 

Set alpha as 0.05|0.1 calculates results for 95% and 90% confidence interval. 


Output
Generate a dataset named final_test (dataset name defined by out) that contains the hazard ratio, 95% and 90% confidence interval and p-value for each age group.
Note the difference in column headers, statistic discriptions are put as column headers while in Example 2, treatment groups are put as column headers.  
The column for reference group is left blank.

macros/utility/m_u_align_decimal/m_u_ali.body:
Example
Example 1 Align decimals for left aligned listings
Example 2 Align decimals for left aligned listings and name variables with prefix

Example 1 Align decimals for left aligned listings
Details
This example does the following:
Align the decimal points for both numeric and character variables AVAL, CHG, and CHGC for input data (adlb), and the output data is _dsout1.
Program
* Call %m_u_align_decimal;
%m_u_align_decimal
    (inds= adlb
    ,outds= __dsout1
    ,var=AVAL#CHG#CHGC
    ,prefix= 
    );

Program Description
Input data feature
Input dataset contains all variables listed in the option var=AVAL#CHG#CHGC. Both numeric and character variables are allowed. Numeric variables AVAL and CHG, and character variable CHGC are included in this example. 

Output
Dataset "work.__inds1.sas7bdat" is created. Original numeric variables AVAL and CHG are output as character variables. Decimals of character variables AVAL, CHG, and CHGC in output dataset are aligned and then final values are left aligned. 

Example 2 Align decimals for left aligned listings and name variables with prefix
Details
This example does the following:
Align the decimal points for both numeric variables AVAL, CHG for input data (adlb), and the output data is _dsout1 where the prefix of aligned variables is "hema". 
Program
* Call %m_u_align_decimal;
%m_u_align_decimal
    (inds= adlb
    ,outds= __dsout
    ,var=AVAL#CHG 
    ,prefix= hema
    );

Program Description
Input data feature
Input data should contain all variables listed in var, including numeric variables AVAL and CHG. Set character prefix as "HEMA" 

Output
Dataset "work.__inds2.sas7bdat" is created. Original numeric variables AVAL and CHG are output as character variables, named HEMA_AVAL and HEMA_CHG. Decimals of character variables HEMA_AVAL and HEMA_CHG are aligned and then final values are left aligned.

macros/utility/m_u_popn/m_u_popn_descp.h.title: m_u_popn
macros/utility/m_u_popn/m_u_popn_descp.h.body:
m_u_popn
Purpose
This utility macro is designed to process a dataset to calculate and generate summary counts for different treatment groups. It allows filtering of the population using a specified condition and can generate formatted macro variables as headers in further analysis or reporting.

The purposes include:

（1）Calculate the number of subjects in each treatment group.
（2）Create macro variables for display headers according to treatment format. Optionally adding (N=XXX) and/or other optional text(e.g., n, n (%)) below the display treatment format.
Note: Treatment format should be created before calling m_u_popn macro.
More details of usage are in Parameter and Example

Output files
After calling this macro, series of global macro variables for BigN and treatment display format are generated and these macro variables can be used across TLF. In this macro, (*ESC*)n is used to split the header.
For example if &gmacro.=saspopb and assume 3 treatments (including total group) need to be displayed.  
（1）Output regardless of BigN and nformat options:

&saspopbN. = 3 [number of treatment groups] 

（2）If BigN=N and nformat is not populated:

&saspopb1. = Group A 
&saspopb2. = Group B 
&saspopb3. = Total

（3）If BigN=N and nformat=n:

&saspopb1. = Group A(*ESC*)nn
&saspopb2. = Group B(*ESC*)nn
&saspopb3. = Total(*ESC*)nn

（4）If BigN=Y and regardless of nformat, will create three series macro variables:

(4.1) Output variables stored counts of each treatment group.

 &saspopbBigN1. = XXX
 &saspopbBigN2. = XXX
 &saspopbBigN3. = XXX

(4.2) Output variables used (*ESC*)n as the split character.

 &saspopbBigNv1. = Group A(*ESC*)nN=XXX
 &saspopbBigNv2. = Group B(*ESC*)nN=XXX
 &saspopbBigNv3. = Total(*ESC*)nN=XXX

(4.3) Output variables used a space as the separated character.

 &saspopbBigNh1. = Group A N=XXX
 &saspopbBigNh2. = Group B N=XXX
 &saspopbBigNh3. = Total N=XXX


（5）If BigN=Y and nformat options are not populated:

 &saspopb1. = Group A(*ESC*)nN=XXX
 &saspopb2. = Group B(*ESC*)nN=XXX
 &saspopb3. = Total(*ESC*)nN=XXX

 （6）If BigN=Y and nformat=%str(n (%%)), %str(n (%%)) will be displayed as n (%) in rtf output:

&saspopb1. = Group A(*ESC*)nN=XXX(*ESC*)nn (%) 
&saspopb2. = Group B(*ESC*)nN=XX(*ESC*)nn (%) 
&saspopb3. = Total(*ESC*)nN=XXX(*ESC*)nn (%)

（7） Output &gmacro.trtlist is based on trtlev [eg. (1|2|1 2) means trtgrpN=1, trtgrpN=2, trtgrpN in (1,2)] and gmacro, and regardless of BigN and nformat options. Total treatment equal to treatment 1 and treatment 2, using space as a seperated. The &gmacro.trtlist could be used to calculate per column groups.

&saspoptrtlist1. =1 
&saspoptrtlist2. =2 
&saspoptrtlist3. =1 2 


Macros used

%m_u_parmchk
%m_u_chkvars
%m_u_chkwhere


Note: entimICE macros, including %m_u_parmchk, %m_u_chkvars, and %m_u_chkwhere are referred when developed O-GEM macros. See entimICEAZ_Mapping_Macros_User_Guide.pdf for further details.

macros/utility/m_u_popn/m_u_popn_examp.h.title: Example
macros/utility/m_u_popn/m_u_popn_examp.h.body:
Example
Example 1 Display treatment group in disposition table
Example 2 Display treatment group with BigN and without other text
Example 3 Display treatment group with BigN and other text
Example 4 Display subtotal and total group-with AZ total

Example 1 Display treatment group in disposition table
Details
This example does the following:
 Create header of treatment without BigN for the template AZTONCSP01A
Program
* Create format;
proc format;
    value _tlf_setup_trtfmt 
    1 = "AZ"
    2 = "Control"
    3 = "Total"
    ;
run;

%m_u_popn(
        inds=adam.adsl
        ,pop_flag=FASFL="Y"  
        ,trtgrpn=TRT01PN
        ,trtlev=1|2|1 2
        ,UniqueIDVars=USUBJID  
         ,trtfmtC=_tlf_setup_trtfmt
         ,gmacro=faspop
         ,BigN=N
        ,nformat=%str(n (%%))
         );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input data includes three required variables: the numeric treatment variable (TRT01PN), the unique subject identifier variable (USUBJID), and the filter condition variable (FASFL).

Parameter description

Display treatment Group
Parameter trtlev=1|2|1 2 provided rules for display treatment groups. In this example, there are 2 orginal treatment groups, and total group (using 1 2 formula for total, separated by a space) are created.  

Treatment group order and text in header
Parameter trtlev=1|2|1 2 also provided treatment group order, treatment group are listed as sequence based on trtlev list treatment order.
trtfmtC=_tlf_setup_trtfmt option provided treatment header text.

n (%) under the treatment group
In this example, set nformat=%str(n %%)) and BigN=N to make (%) appear below treatment label and no BigN needed.


Output
Set gmacro=FASpop then output global varibales of FASpopn, FASpop1-FASpop3, and FASpoptrtlist1-FASpoptrtlist3. These global macro  variables can be used in dispostition table.



Example 2 Display treatment group with BigN and without other text
Details
This example does the following:
 Create header of formatted treatment with BigN and without other display text.
Program
* Create format;
proc format;
    value _tlf_setup_trtfmt 
    1 = "AZ"
    2 = "Control"
    3 = "Total"
    ;
run;

%m_u_popn(
        inds=adam.adsl
        ,pop_flag= SAFFL="Y"  
        ,trtgrpn=TRT01AN
        ,trtlev=1|2|1 2
        ,UniqueIDVars= USUBJID
         ,trtfmtC=_tlf_setup_trtfmt
         ,gmacro=SASpopb
         ,BigN=Y
        ,nformat= 
         );

Program Description
  Similar to Example 1 but by providing the pop_flag= SAFFL="Y" condition and trtgrpn=TRT01AN to change the population, and set BigN=Y and nformat= to calcalate BigN and make other text below treatment lable disappear.
  
Output
 Similar to Example 1, set gmacro=SASpopb, series of global macro variables are produced. In addition to SASpopbn, SASpopb1-SASpopb3, SASpopbtrtlist1-SASpopbtrtlist3, other macro variables SASpopbbign1-SASpopbbign3, SASpopbbignv1-SASpopbbignv3,SASpopbbignh1-SASpopbbignh3 are also generated. These global macro variables can be used in other reports, such as duration of exposure table AZTONCEX01 .



Example 3 Display treatment group with BigN and other text
Details
This example does the following:
Create header of formatted treatment with BigN and n (%) display text.
Program
* Create format;

proc format;
    value _tlf_setup_trtfmt 
    1 = "Group A"
    2 = "Group B"
    3 = "Total"
    ;
run;

%m_u_popn(
        inds=adam.adsl
        ,pop_flag= SAFFL="Y"  
        ,trtgrpn=TRT01AN
        ,trtlev=1|2|1 2
        ,UniqueIDVars= USUBJID
         ,trtfmtC=_tlf_setup_trtfmt
         ,gmacro=SASpopb
         ,BigN=Y
        ,nformat=  %str(n (%%))
         );

Program Description
  Similar to Example 2 but by providing the nformat=  %str(n (%%)) to display n (%) below treatment lable.
  
Output
 Similar to Example 2, set gmacro=SASpopb, series of global macro variables, including SASpopbn, SASpopb1-SASpopb3, SASpopbtrtlist1-SASpopbtrtlist3, SASpopbbign1-SASpopbbign3, SASpopbbignv1-SASpopbbignv3,SASpopbbignh1-SASpopbbignh3 are generated. These global macro variables can be used in other reports, such as summary of adverse events table AZTONCAE01A.



Example 4 Display subtotal and total group-with AZ total
Details
This example does the following:

Create format of treatments, treatment groups include subtotal and total.
Create global variables for treatment groups, including subtotal and total groups.  

Program
* Create format;
proc format;
    *Display text in table Header;
    value _tlf_setup_trtfmtb  
    1 = "AZD1 >"
    2 = "AZD2 >"
    3 = "AZ Total"
    4 = "Control"
    5 = "Total"
    ;             
run;
%m_u_popn(
    inds=adsl
    ,pop_flag=SAFFL="Y"  
    ,trtgrpn=TRT01AN
    ,trtlev=1|2|1 2|3|1 2 3 
    ,UniqueIDVars= USUBJID 
    ,trtfmtC=_tlf_setup_trtfmtb
    ,gmacro=SASpopb
    ,BigN=Y
    ,nformat=%str(n (%%)) 
    );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input data includes three required variables: the numeric treatment variable (TRT01AN), the unique subject identifier variable (USUBJID), and the fit condition variable (FASFL). Note that there are only 3 treatment levels  in input dataset (TRT01AN=1: AZD1; TRT01AN=2: AZD2; TRT01AN=3: Control).

Parameter description

Subtotal/Total
Parameter trtlev=1|2|1 2|3|1 2 3 provided rules for subtotal and total group. In this example, subtotal AZ group (using 1 2 formula for subtotal, separated by a space) is insert before control group. Total Group (using 1 2 3 formula for total, separated by a space) is displayed as the last column.  

Treatment group order and text in header
Parameter trtlev=1|2|1 2|3|1 2 3 also provided treatment group order, treatment group are listed as sequence. In this example, there are 5 level treatment groups in total.
trtfmtC=_tlf_setup_trtfmtb provided treatment header lable based on trtlev=1|2|1 2|3|1 2 3 list treatment order.

BigN display format
In this example, BigN value and (%) appear below treatment label when BigN=Y and nformat=%str(n %%)).


Output
Set gmacro=SASpopb, series of global macro variables, including SASpopbn, SASpopb1-SASpopb5, SASpopbtrtlist1-SASpopbtrtlist5, SASpopbbign1-SASpopbbign5, SASpopbbignv1-SASpopbbignv5,SASpopbbignh1-SASpopbbignh5 are generated. These global macro variables can be used in other reports, such as summary of adverse events table AZTONCAE01A.

macros/utility/m_u_popn/m_u_popn_error.h.title: Common Error
macros/utility/m_u_popn/m_u_popn_error.h.body:
Common Error
Check Mandatory and Conditional values
Note: Mandatory parameters inds, trtgrpn，trtfmtC, trtlev, gmacro are required and should be stated.

ERROR: (M_U_POPN) (m_u_parmchk) Required parameter inds is missing
ERROR: (M_U_POPN) (m_u_parmchk) Required parameter trtgrpn is missing
ERROR: (M_U_POPN) (m_u_parmchk) Required parameter trtfmtC is missing
ERROR: (M_U_POPN) (m_u_parmchk) Required parameter trtlev is missing
ERROR: (M_U_POPN) (m_u_parmchk) Required parameter gmacro is missing

Check exist dataset and variables
Note: input data inds must exist and can be open to check the valid values.

ERROR:(M_U_POPN) (M_U_CHKVARS) Dataset inds does not exist
ERROR:(M_U_POPN) (M_U_CHKVARS) Open for dataset inds failed

Note: input variable UniqueIDVars and trtgrpn must exist in dsin dataset. Otherwise, will trigger the following alert (&&strl&chkvarsI. is the variable name being checked). 

ERROR: (M_U_POPN) Variable &&strl&chkvarsI.does not exist in &inds

Check where condition
Note: If pop_flag is populated, fiter conditons should be correctly applied in dsin dataset. Otherwise, will trigger the following alert. 

ERROR: (M_U_POPN) (M_U_CHKWHERE)  WHERE=pop_flag is not correct, check variables

Check others
 Note: trtfmtC is the display header for outputs, and the level should be keep consistent with trtlev, trtlev=1|2|1 2|3|1 2 3 as an example, there are 5 levels in the header, then trtfmtC should also has 5 display header format. 

ERROR: (M_U_POPN) Parameter 'trtfmtC' has fewer levels than 'trtlev'[&trtlev.]. Please check input values.

 Note: The order of trtfmtC format should be created as sequence. trtlev=1|2|1 2|3|1 2 3 as an example, there are 5 levels in the header, Level of trtfmtC starts from 1 to 5, 3 stands for subtotal(treatment: 1 2) and 5 stands for totol(treatment: 1 2 3 ). The Maximum number of treatment group is 5. If other level number is assigned for total group, such as 99, for example the number of levels of trtfmtC is 5, but Maximum level of parameter is 99, this suitation will trigger this error.

ERROR: (MU_POPN) Maximum level of parameter 'trtfmtC'[&max__grpn.] is different from the number of levels[&_trtfmtC_N.].

Item
Contents




Default

Requirement
Mandatory


Restriction



Interaction



Eg.
adsl adam.adsl



lenlist
specifies the width proportion for each column. The lengths should be separated by "#" and their sum should be less than or equal to 99 per page. If this parameter is not provided, then column length will be calculated in macro automatically. The current algorithm for automatically calculating column widths is not yet mature enough. It is recommended that users manually adjust based on the output situation of RTF.

macros/utility/m_u_report/m_u_report_exa.title: Example
macros/utility/m_u_report/m_u_report_exa.body:
Example
Example 1 Report for table
Example 2 Report for listing

Example 1 Report for table
Details
This example does the following:
Used dataset which is generated by %m_t_nested to report a table.
Program

%m_u_report(table=final2output
    ,lenlist=5#2#2#2
      ,justlist=l#c#c#c
      ,justlist_header=l#c#c#c
      ,nolblist=N#N#N#N
      ,blank_after=blank_after_SEQ
    ,pg=15
    );

Program Description
Input data feature
Final2output dataset is generated by %m_t_nested. This dataset contains COL1-COL4 (which are displayed as the table content), PAGE (which is used as the page variable), and blank_after_SEQ (insert blank line after the same values based on this variable).

Parameter feature

The lenlist is set to "5#2#2#2", means that the width ratio for COL1-COL4 is 5:2:2:2.
The justlist is set to "l#c#c#c", means that the COL1's content is left-aligned, COL2 to COL4 are center-aligned.
The justlist_header is set to "l#c#c#c", means that the header of COL1 is left-aligned, COL2 to COL4 are center-aligned.
The nolblist is set to "N#N#N#N", means that every column header is displayed.
The blank_after is set to "blank_after_SEQ", means that blank line is insert after the same value of blank_after_SEQ.
The pg is set to "15", new page is generated when line number>15.

Output
Table is displayed.


Example 2 Report for listing
Details
This example does the following:
Used dataset which is generated by %m_l to report a listing.
Program

%m_u_report(table=final2output
    ,lenlist=
      ,justlist=l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l
      ,justlist_header=l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l
      ,nolblist=N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N
      ,idlist=Y#Y#Y
      ,idpage=N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#Y
    ,pg=15
    );

Program Description
Input data feature
Final2output dataset is generated by %m_l. This dataset contains COL1-COL16 (which are displayed as listing content), PAGE (which is used as page variable), and BYVAR (which is used to display subtitle).

Parameter description
The example is a listing with 16 columns.

The justlist option is set to "l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l", namely the content is left-aligned in all columns.
The justlist_header option is set to "l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l#l", namely the header is left-aligned in all columns.
The nolblist option is set to "N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N", namely every column header is displayed.
The idlist option is set to "Y#Y#Y", means that the last "Y" column (column 3), and all columns to its right appear at the left of every page.
The idpage option is set to "N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#N#Y", means that the column 10 is set to "Y", therefore, this column and the columns to its right will be displayed on the next page. Given that the idlist option had been defined as display the first 3 columns, the final display will be as follow: The first page display column 1 to 9; The second page display column 1 to 3, 10 to 16.

Output
Listing is displayed. Start a new page from column 10, and column 1-column 3 are ID variables and appear at the left of every page.

macros/utility/m_u_tlf_md/m_u_tlf_md_des.title: m_u_tlf_md
macros/utility/m_u_tlf_md/m_u_tlf_md_des.body:
m_u_tlf_md
Purpose
This utility macro is designed to create the TLF metadata and also create needed TLF generation codes.
The purposes include:
(1) Create the TLF metadata
Convert toc index.xlsx into TLF.titles which could be used in %istartv2 and %istopv2 to report rtf output. The toc index file should have one observation per one TLF. If need to display page-by outputs, then title 7 should be set "j=L '#byval(byvar)'".  
(2) Create needed TLF generation codes
(2.1) For those TLF programs already covered in O-GEM, the example TLF generation codes will be copied to study folder directly. 
(2.2) For those not covered, a blank program with basic info such as program header, %setup, %localsetup will be generated named as defined in toc index file. 
(2.3) A batch run code with log check 'batch_tfl.sas' could also be generated. 

More details of usage are in Parameter and Example.

Output files
 After calling this macro, a sas7bdat file named tlf.titles is generated. This dataset contains PROGRAM (program names), SUFFIX (used to name the output files), PARAM (including title, footnote, and outfile), and the values of each Parameters.  




Macros used

%runpgm
%m_u_varexist
%u_blank


Note: entimICE macros %runpgm is referred when developed O-GEM macros. See %runpgm macro in entimICE: root/cdar/common/gmd/prod/macro for further details.

Used in

Not used in other macros.

macros/utility/m_u_tlf_md/m_u_tlf_md_exa.title: Example
macros/utility/m_u_tlf_md/m_u_tlf_md_exa.body:
Example
Example 1 Use title1 and title2 in toc index file
Example 2 Use title1 and title2 as additional specifications
Example 3 Generate codes for each TLF in toc index file

Example 1 Use title1 and title2 in toc index file
Details
This example does the following:
Create tlf.titles metadata from toc index file, including title1 and title2.
Program
* Call %m_u_tlf_md;
%m_u_tlf_md(
    filein=root/cdar/xxx/xxxx/ar/xx/tlf/doc/toc_index.xlsx,
    sheet=Index,
    _all_= N,
    title1=,
    title2=,
    pgmgen=N,
    prgmpath=,
    repopath=,
    batch=N,
    error_override=,
    deBug=N
    );

Program Description
Input toc index file contains title1 and title2. _all_=N must be provided.

Output
TLF.titles dataset is created and title1 and title2 are created from toc file.


Example 2 Use title1 and title2 as additional specifications
Details
This example does the following:
Create tlf.titles metadata from toc index file, however, title 1 and title 2 information are not presented in toc (or will not use title 1 and title 2 in toc) and require additional provision.
Program
 * Call %m_u_tlf_md;
%m_u_tlf_md(
    filein=root/cdar/xxx/xxxx/ar/xx/tlf/doc/toc_index.xlsx,
    sheet=Index,
    _all_= Y,
    title1= %str(j=l 'AstraZeneca') ,
    title2= %str(j=l 'D0000C00001'),
    pgmgen=N,
    prgmpath=,
    repopath=,
    batch=N,
    error_override=,
    deBug=N
);

Program Description 
When _all_=Y, then title1 and title2 must be provided. Other TLF metadata information (except for title1 and title2) is created from the toc_index.xlsx. 
Output
Title1 and title2 are added in tlf.titles.


Example 3 Generate codes for each TLF in toc index file
Details
This example does the following:
Create tlf codes according to toc and generate batch_tlf.sas
Program
* Call %m_u_tlf_md;
%m_u_tlf_md(
    filein=root/cdar/xxx/xxxx/ar/xx/tlf/doc/toc_index.xlsx,
    sheet=Index,
    _all_= N,
    title1= ,
    title2= ,
    pgmgen= Y ,
    prgmpath= root/cdar/xxx/xxxx/ar/xx/tlf/dev/program,
    repopath= root/global_tools/oncology/o_gem/pgm/pilot_core/tlf/dev/program,
    dev/program,
    batch=Y,
    error_override=N,
    deBug=N
    );

Program Description
Set pgmgen=Y, parameters of prgmpath, batch, and error_override are all provided. prgmpath provide location of generated codes. repopath provide the developed O-GEM codes as reference, and codes will be copied to prgmpath location. If TLF codes are not existed in prgmpath and not in repopath, then blank codes will be generated. 
Output
Batch_tlf.sas and program codes are generated.

macros/utility/m_u_tlf_md/m_u_tlf_md_err.title: Common Error
macros/utility/m_u_tlf_md/m_u_tlf_md_err.body:
Common Error
Check Mandatory columns in excel sheet
Note: PROGRAM, SUFFIX,OUTFILE columns are required and must exist in toc index file.

ERROR: [m_u_tlf_md]NO Mandatory column PROGRAM in "&filein."
ERROR: [m_u_tlf_md]NO Mandatory column SUFFIX in "&filein."
ERROR: [m_u_tlf_md]NO Mandatory column OUTFILE in "&filein."

Check Mandatory values in excel sheet
Note: PROGRAM column is required and value can not be missing.

ERROR: (m_u_tlf_md)PROGRAM has missing value.

Note: TITLE3 column should not be exist in toc index file. If exist, then title3 should be null.

ERROR: (m_u_tlf_md)TITLE3 should be null.

Check number of titles and footnote
Note: If a subtitle is needed by page, then total titles can be >6, otherwise, Maximum number of TITLEs should not be greater than 6. Maximum number of footnotes should not be greater than 9. Otherwise, will trigger the following alert. 

WARNING: Maximum number of TITLEs is>6 (without by page). Please check.
WARNING: Maximum number of FOOTNOTEs is>9. Please check.

Check Others
Note: Macro check folder of &prgmpath (usually location of generated codes) or &repopath (usually location of the developed O-GEM codes) should be exist. Otherwise, will trigger the following alert. 

ERROR: Macro variable dir is empty, please include folder path.

macros/utility/m_u_effcount/m_u_effcount.title: Example
macros/utility/m_u_effcount/m_u_effcount.body:
Example
Example 1 Calculate counts and percentages without additional denominator dataset
Example 2 Calculate counts and percentages with specified denominator dataset
Example 1 Calculate counts and percentages without additional denominator dataset
Details
This example does the following: 
Calculate counts and percentages based on index information. 
Program
%m_u_effcount(inds= adam.adtte
                            , pop_flag= ITTFL="Y"
                            , whr= paramcd='TRPROGM' and parqual='INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR'
                            , trtgrpn= trt01pn
                            , denomds= 
                            , pop_mvar= ITTpopb
                            , index= {cond=CNSR=0 # label=%nrbquote(Total events [a], n (%)) #level=0 subord=1}
                                     {cond=cnsr=0 and find(evntdesc,'RECIST progression') label=RECIST progression level=1 subord=2}
                                     {cond=cnsr=0 and find(evntdesc,'RECIST progression with target') label=Target lesion [b] level=2 subord=3}
                                     {cond=cnsr=1 label=%nrbquote(Censored patients, n (%)) level=0 subord=4}
                                     {cond=cnsr=1 and find(evntdesc,'Censored RECIST progression') label=Censored RECIST progression [c] level=1 subord=5}
                            , statlabel= Y
                            , denomcond=
                            , ord= 1
                            , debug= N
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset can be any dataset that is not empty and contains variables to be analyzed such as trtgrpn and variables specified in where condition.
In this example, we are using a standard ADAM adtte dataset.

Parameter description

inds specifies the input dataset name, the output dataset is defaulted to name final_effcount_.

index parameter contains information of condition, suborder, level and label for each row.  {cond=cnsr=0 and find(evntdesc,'RECIST progression with target') label=Target lesion [b] level=2 subord=3} indicates that in this row, we want to count numer of people that satisfies this condition: cnsr=0 and find(evntdesc,'RECIST progression with target').  label=Target lesion [b] means the display label for this row should be Target lesion [b].  level = 2 indicates that this row is a sub-level and should have one indentation.  subord=3 represents that it should be the third line within the output dataset.


Output
Generate a dataset, name defined by final_effcount_, with counts and percentages statistics.
 
In this example, ITTpopb in m_u_popn defined three treatment groups: 1|2|1 2.  However, in trtgrpn variable, only 1 and 2 exist. Thus, col3 in the output dataset has zero values.
 
Example 2 Calculate counts and percentages with specified denominator dataset
Details
This example does the following: 
Calculate counts and percentages based on index information with specified denominator dataset. 
Program
%m_u_effcount(inds= adam.adtte
                            , pop_flag= ITTFL="Y"
                            , whr= paramcd='TRPROGM' and parqual='INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR'
                            , trtgrpn= trt01pn
                            , denomds= ADSL_partial
                            , pop_mvar= ITTpopb
                            , index= {cond=CNSR=0 # label=%nrbquote(Total events [a], n (%)) #level=0 subord=1}
                                     {cond=cnsr=0 and find(evntdesc,'RECIST progression') label=RECIST progression level=1 subord=2}
                                     {cond=cnsr=0 and find(evntdesc,'RECIST progression with target') label=Target lesion [b] level=2 subord=3}
                                     {cond=cnsr=1 label=%nrbquote(Censored patients, n (%)) level=0 subord=4}
                                     {cond=cnsr=1 and find(evntdesc,'Censored RECIST progression') label=Censored RECIST progression [c] level=1 subord=5}
                            , statlabel= Y
                            , denomcond=
                            , ord= 1
                            , debug= N
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset can be any dataset that is not empty and contains variables to be analyzed such as trtgrpn and variables specified in where condition.
In this example, we are using a standard ADAM adtte dataset.

Parameter description

inds specifies the input dataset name, the output dataset is defaulted to name final_effcount_.

denomds defines the denominator dataset to use. This overwrites the total big N calculated in m_u_popn.



index parameter contains information of condition, suborder, level and label for each row.  {cond=cnsr=0 and find(evntdesc,'RECIST progression with target') label=Target lesion [b] level=2 subord=3} indicates that in this row, we want to count numer of people that satisfies this condition: cnsr=0 and find(evntdesc,'RECIST progression with target').  label=Target lesion [b] means the display label for this row should be Target lesion [b].  level = 2 indicates that this row is a sub-level and should have one indentation.  subord=3 represents that it should be the third line within the output dataset.

Output
Generate a dataset, name defined by final_effcount_, with counts and percentages statistics.  In this example, denominator dataset is defined (denomds= ADSL_partial) and it is a subset of the original adam.adsl.  Note that the calculated percentage is bigger than the result from exmaple 1 as a result of smaller denominator value.
 
In this example, ITTpopb in m_u_popn defined three treatment groups: 1|2|1 2.  However, in trtgrpn variable, only 1 and 2 exist. Thus, col3 in the output dataset has zero values.

macros/utility/m_u_col_header/m_u_col_he.title: Example
macros/utility/m_u_col_header/m_u_col_he.body:
Example
Example 1 Append headers onto columns manually
Example 2 Append headers onto columns using m_u_popn generated variables

Example 1 Append headers onto columns manually
Details
This example does the following:
Append headers onto columns in the input dataset by utilizing collabel.
Program
%m_u_col_header(inds=   rawdata
                            , outds= finaldata
                            , gmacro= 
                            , modcol=
                            , collabel= col1='USUBJID' col2='SEX' col3='AGE'
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset needs to contain columns with values.
Note that currently there are no labels.

Parameter description

inds,outds specifies the input and output dataset names.

collabel defines the labels that will be applied onto the dataset. Please make sure all columns defined in collabel exist within the inds dataset.


Output
Generate a dataset name defined by outds where labels are applied to the corresponding columns.
 
Example 2 Append headers onto columns using gmacro
Details
This example does the following:
Append headers onto columns in the input dataset by utilizing gmacro.
Program
%m_u_col_header(inds=   rawdata
                            , outds= finaldata
                            , gmacro= saspopb
                            , modcol= 1
                            , collabel= col1='USUBJID'
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset needs to contain columns with values.
Note that currently there are no labels.

Parameter description

inds,outds specifies the input and output dataset names.

gmacro defines the group that will be used within m_u_popn. 
modcol defines the number difference between treatment group number and column number.


Output
Generate a dataset name defined by outds where labels are applied to the corresponding columns.
In this example, there are 2 treatment groups and I want to apply the header onto col2 and col3. Thus, modcol is set to 1 to accommodate for the difference.
Since m_u_popn only generates headers for treatment groups, we still need to define header for col1 manually within collabel.

Details
This example does the following:
Reorganize columns that follows naming convention (column name MUST start with prefix col) into default column names (col1 col2 col3 etc.).
Program
%m_u_col_reorg(inds=   rawdata
                            , outds= finaldata
                            , colin= 
                            , colout=
                            , keep=
                            );

Program Description
Input data feature
The input dataset needs to contain columns that follows naming convention. 
Very important: column name MUST start with prefix col. 

Parameter description

inds,outds specifies the input and output dataset names.

When colin and colout are left blank, the output dataset column names will be set as default.


Output
Generate a dataset name defined by outds with columns reorganized.

Input data feature
The input dataset needs to contain columns that follows naming convention.

Other
Other macros are utilized to facilitate the development of the macro suite and do not fall into the categories of utility, analysis, or display macros.

other/u_blank.html.title: u_blank
other/u_blank.html.body:
u_blank
This is a standard template for blank SAS code. When pgmgen=Y is required in %m_u_tlf_md, the corresponding programming codes for TLF are generated based on this template. The standard structure includes a program header, study-level setup section, and three predefined step sections.

Headers are to include the following details.




Item
Contents




Program name
&filename.


Program path
&_exec_programpath.


Type
TLF generation code


Purpose



Author
&_exec_userid.


Date created
%scan(&_exec_programlastmodified,1,"T")


Input datasets



Macros used



Output files



Revision history





Note: For generated codes, Program name, Program path, Author, and Date created are automatically generate when calling %m_u_tlf_md.


Study-level setup section
Including %setup macro and a %localsetup macro.


Three predefined step sections are to include the following details.%** Step1. Proc format used in TLF **;
%** Step2. Data preprocessing **;
%** Step3. Call display macros **;
